org.wiredwidgets.rem2.schema

Class NodeType

  • java.lang.Object
    • org.wiredwidgets.rem2.schema.NodeType

  • public class NodeType
extends Object
    The structure of this type follows the structure of the Jackrabbit custom_nodetypes.xml configuration file. This leads to some unfortunate method naming in JAXB generateed code, such as isIsQueryable().

    Java class for NodeType complex type.

    The following schema fragment specifies the expected content contained within this class. 

     <complexType name="NodeType">
   <complexContent>
     <restriction base="{http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema}anyType">
       <sequence>
         <element name="childNode" type="{http://www.wiredwidgets.org/rem2/schema}NodeDefinition" maxOccurs="unbounded" minOccurs="0"/>
         <element name="supertypes" type="{http://www.wiredwidgets.org/rem2/schema}Supertypes" minOccurs="0"/>
         <element name="propertyDefinition" type="{http://www.wiredwidgets.org/rem2/schema}PropertyDefinition" maxOccurs="unbounded" minOccurs="0"/>
       </sequence>
       <attribute name="name" use="required" type="{http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema}string" />
       <attribute name="primaryItemName" type="{http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema}string" />
       <attribute name="hasOrderableChildNodes" type="{http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema}boolean" default="false" />
       <attribute name="isAbstract" type="{http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema}boolean" default="false" />
       <attribute name="isMixin" type="{http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema}boolean" default="false" />
       <attribute name="isQueryable" type="{http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema}boolean" default="false" />
     </restriction>
   </complexContent>
 </complexType>

      • getChildNodes

        public List<NodeDefinition> getChildNodes()
        Gets the value of the childNodes property.

        This accessor method returns a reference to the live list, not a snapshot. Therefore any modification you make to the returned list will be present inside the JAXB object. This is why there is not a set method for the childNodes property.

        For example, to add a new item, do as follows: 

            getChildNodes().add(newItem);

        Objects of the following type(s) are allowed in the list NodeDefinition
